The article is a presidential proclamation by Barack Obama declaring October 9, 2013, as Leif Erikson Day. The proclamation highlights the journey of Leif Erikson, a son of Iceland and grandson of Norway, who inadvertently became the first European to visit North America when his ship drifted off course and landed in present-day Canada. The proclamation also honors a group of Norwegian immigrants who arrived in New York City in 1825, symbolizing the spirit of exploration and opportunity that America represents. The proclamation emphasizes America's history as a place of promise and celebrates the contributions of Norwegian Americans to the country. The proclamation concludes by calling upon all Americans to observe Leif Erikson Day with appropriate ceremonies and activities to honor the Nordic-American heritage.